I used to give myself a LOT of credit for my marriage to @lisabilyeu. I thought, damn, man... I’m GOOD at this. And then it hit me... the statement that 80% of a successful relationship is selection. 

You have to choose the right partner. A high functioning relationship will be the greatest joy of your life - something well worth great sacrifice to protect and nurture. But a dysfunctional relationship will completely dismantle your life. 

Before you embark on the journey of rebuilding, make sure that you’re rebuilding the right relationship. If this is the right relationship - amazing! Go on in repairing. But, man... if it’s not. If you’re in a relationship with someone who has contempt for you or you have contempt for them, I advise you to face head on that this may not be the right relationship to save. 

Just keep in mind, your partner is looking at you the same way. You both have to be worth fighting for. 

For anyone out there struggling, I’m sending you good vibes and hoping that you can build a better situation for yourself - with your current partner or without them. 

But don’t think your worth is tied up in making it work. You’ve only got one shot at life, so make sure you’re building something that lifts you and those around you up. I’m sending all the love in the world. 

For @lisabilyeu ’s take on this be sure to subscribe to our Relationship Theory YouTube channel. We go deep on all of this stuff. Link in bio.

node.text:
When I think about who I was back when the photo on the left was taken I can't even begin to relate.

I'm not saying that we're born blank slates - we're definitely not. But I am saying that while you might be born with certain hardware we all decide what operating system we're going to run.

Where it gets complicated is that we don't always choose what operating system we install.

What I mean by that is, our youth is by far the most important time in our lives in terms of what shapes our perceptions, beliefs, attitudes, values, etc.

And it's all happening at a time when we're too young to understand that we have a choice in what we decide to believe and make a part of our operating system.

We don't yet have a perspective that allows us to recognize that there are a million ways to interpret the things that happen to us.

And so we get stuck thinking that the things we believe about ourselves and the world around us are objectively true when in reality they're just things we believe to be true.

My adult life has been a complicated process of both learning and unlearning.

We all have to take a super honest look at the things we believe and figure out which beliefs are moving us towards our goals and which beliefs are holding us back.

I will tell you one thing that held me back for years. It's something that I know is holding many people reading this back as well. I thought I was too stupid to succeed.

I thought that because life had proven to me that that was true.

But then I became obsessed with the notion that humans are designed to adapt.

Put them under enough pressure and they will grow. Logically, if that applied to humans as a species generally, then it must apply to me specifically.

That realization changed my entire belief system.

The question is, what unhelpful belief are you holding onto that if you let go of would change your whole life?

Identify that, make the change, and watch yourself grow.

And if you want help to identify and replace those limiting beliefs with empowering ones, join me in Impact Theory University where I teach a whole masterclass on the subject called Mindset 101.

Sign up now and I'll see you there! Link in bio🔝

My wife @lisabilyeu and I have been together for nearly 20 years, and we’ve learned one immutable truth - people waste a lot of time arguing about dumb shit. ⁣
⁣
We certainly did. ⁣
⁣
But there are ways to avoid it. ⁣
⁣
You can see above some of our rules of engagement. ⁣
⁣
The key is to let go of the freakishly intense human desire to be right. ⁣
⁣
And you’ve got to let go of any bitterness or resentment you have with each other and fill your heart with love (yes, I’m aware of how dumb that sounds). ⁣
⁣
As science has shown, contempt for your partner is the number one predictor of a future breakup. ⁣
⁣
You’ve got to find a way past the bullshit, to letting things go, to joy and connection. ⁣
⁣
Otherwise, why bother? ⁣
⁣
If you want to hear more about how to change the game in your relationship, head over to Relationship Theory on YouTube (link in bio).

And if you’ve got some amazing tips for me, drop them in the comments! I’m always game to learn new stuff!

node.text:
The temptation is always to avoid the hard things.⁣
⁣
I get it, in the moment it’s no big deal. But those moments add up and they become who you are.⁣
⁣
Do the hard things. But check yourself. See where you’re really at. No judgement.⁣
⁣
Just see, and remember, you can always improve. So many people hide from who they really are and that’s the surest way to lose respect for yourself and to be haunted by your subconscious.⁣
⁣
We have psychological mechanisms built into our emotional reward system honed over millions of years of evolution that propel us to develop ourselves. Ignore them at your peril.

SWIPE LEFT 👈⁣

I’m always surprised by just how differently different people use different words. ⁣
⁣
It really will save you a lot of suffering to take the time to define a handful of words. ⁣
⁣
It doesn’t have to be the same words that @lisabilyeu and I have defined, but they should be words that lay a solid foundation for communication. ⁣
⁣
You need to be able to effectively  communicate your needs and the intensity level of any request. ⁣
⁣
You need a word that lets you cut through someone’s insecurities or address a surprising reaction. ⁣
⁣
For us that word is “promise”. ⁣
⁣
If one of us says “I promise” then we know it’s gospel truth. ⁣
⁣
If I tell Lisa she looks hot in something, or that a piece of art she’s created is amazing, or she killed it in a business meeting, but she thinks I’m just being nice, I can hit her with “I promise”. ⁣
⁣
She’ll instantly know I mean it. ⁣
⁣
The key with all of these defined terms is to NEVER abuse them. ⁣
⁣
You can’t make someone promise after every statement they make, and you can’t just say everything is important. ⁣
⁣
That shit has to be rare. ⁣
⁣
And both people in the relationship must be respectful of the underlying purpose of these words. ⁣
⁣
They’re not meant to be weapons. ⁣
⁣
If one person says “X is important to me.” ⁣
⁣
The other person shouldn’t turn around in a huff and say, “Well Y is important to me!” ⁣
⁣
In fact, chances are, if that happens you’re actually dealing with a collision of values, and that’s what you should be talking about. 😉 ⁣
⁣
This is definitely advanced class stuff, but it is worth mastering.⁣

For more relationship advice, head over to our YouTube channel, Relationship Theory. Link in bio 👆
